  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Faster AUM deployment:</strong> If transaction environments recover fully and Blackstone deploys its record dry powder rapidly, management fees and carry could surge.</li>
    <li><strong>Private wealth expansion:</strong> Continued penetration into the retail / private wealth channel could provide a massive, sticky source of new capital.</li>
    <li><strong>New asset classes:</strong> Successful scaling of newer strategies like energy transition could accelerate top-line growth.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest rates:</strong> Higher for longer rates could depress real estate valuations and make financing buyouts more difficult.</li>
    <li><strong>Fundraising slowdown:</strong> Institutional allocators hitting their caps for private markets could stall AUM growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory scrutiny:</strong> Increasing regulation on private credit or antitrust oversight on roll-ups could increase compliance costs.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF for an asset manager like Blackstone?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While AUM or fee-related earnings (FRE) multiples are common, a DCF captures the ultimate cash generated by the business. It requires assumptions on growth and risk, creating a more robust framework than point-in-time multiples.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 10% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Given the 10-year Treasury yield of 4.18% (March 2026), a 10% discount rate incorporates an adequate equity risk premium for a blue-chip financial firm. It represents a solid required return for investors.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

